{"meta":{"domain":"subjects","kid":"5153","authors":[{"fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre","id":"6"}],"title":"","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:29 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:29 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"body":"<p class=\"Paragraph\">Like other nominalizers, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ས་</span> can form nominal clauses as well as relative clauses. This nominalizer relates to the <strong>location </strong>or the <strong>goal </strong>of the verbal action. (In other words, the suffix indicates locative adverbials and indirect objects.)</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འབྲི་ས་</span> “The place where one writes, or upon which one writes”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཕུལ་ས་</span> (<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འབུལ་ས་</span>) “The place where one makes an offering,” “the person to whom one makes an offering”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཞུ་ས་</span> “The person to whom one speaks,” “the place where one speaks”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཉལ་ས་</span> “The place where one sleeps”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འགྲོ་ས་</span> “The place toward which one goes,” “the trail”</li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">The verb to which the suffix ས་ is attached appears in the present-future stem form, but it may be used in the context of the past, present, or future:</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཞུ་ས་</span> but not *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཞུས་ས་</span></li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཟ་ས་</span> but not *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཟས་ས་</span></li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བལྟ་ས་</span> but not *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བལྟས་ས་</span></li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Formulations with <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ས་</span> are very common in Tibetan, and may sometimes be translated by nouns in European languages.</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འདིར་བསྡད་ས་(སྡོད་ས་)འདུག་གས།</span> “Is there a room here?” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">སྣུམ་བླླུག་ས་ག་པར་འདུག</span> “Where’s the gas station?”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">སྤ་སེ་ཉོ་ས་ཕ་གིར་འདུག</span> “The ticket office is over there.”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འདི་ཇ་འཐུང་ས་རེད་པས།</span> “Is that a teashop?” Or, “Is that a teacup?” </li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">In these examples, the four substantives “room,” “gas station,” “ticket office,” and “teacup” would be translated literally as “sitting place,” “gasoline pouring place,” “ticket buying place,” and “tea drinking place.”</p> <p class=\"Paragraph\">The nominalizer <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ས་</span> provides no clues about the tense-aspect of the verb, which has to be deduced from the context.</p>","title":""}]}
